      <a href="https://orangette.net/2006/03/a-public-display-of-chickpeas/#comment-3765"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2011-04-10T19:21:12-04:00">Sunday, April 10, 2011 at 7:21 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Molly and Brandon I can&#39;t thank you enough for this recipe. It is so perfect for bringing meals to families will new little bundles or if they&#39;ve caught a bit of a cold or some other ailment. It freezes beautifully and gets better with each day.<br />Making a large batch today in fact.<br />Thanks!!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-3766" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2006/03/a-public-display-of-chickpeas/#comment-3766"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2011-06-27T02:34:00-04:00">Monday, June 27, 2011 at 2:34 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Fresh mango and grated baby carrots along with a good tomato paste give the necessary sweetness to off-set the spice and tart tastes of lemon juice, garam masala, cumin, coriander, curry, anaheim chiles and red chili flakes that I use in my chana. The grated ginger, chopped onions and garlic and ribbons of Thai basil along with cilantro add the final touches to the chickpeas, vegetable broth and coconut milk. Just make sure to heat the spices and herbs with a good quality olive oil to begin.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-3768" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Anonymous</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2006/03/a-public-display-of-chickpeas/#comment-3768"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2011-06-27T02:34:00-04:00">Monday, June 27, 2011 at 2:34 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Fresh mango and grated baby carrots along with a good tomato paste give the necessary sweetness to off-set the spice and tart tastes of lemon juice, garam masala, cumin, coriander, curry, anaheim chiles and red chili flakes that I use in my chana. The grated ginger, chopped onions and garlic and ribbons of Thai basil along with cilantro add the final touches to the chickpeas, vegetable broth and coconut milk. Just make sure to heat the spices and herbs with a good quality olive oil to begin.</p>
    </div>

